erences==\n{{reflist}}\n{{1986 films}}\n\n[[Category:1986 films|*LGBT]]\n[[Category:1986 in LGBT history]]\n[[Category:Lists of LGBT-related films by year|1986]]\n[[Category:1980s LGBT-related films|*1986]]\n", "name_user": "Laandrade", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_LGBT-related_films_of_1986"}
{"title_page": "Xandra Ibarra", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Xandra Ibarra\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| alt                = Xandra Ibarra\n| caption            = Xandra Ibarra, \"Spictacle II: La Tortillera.\" Documentation of live performance at Hemispheric Institute Encuentro, 2014\n| other_names        = La Chica Boom\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth year and age|1979}}\n| birth_place        = El Paso/Juarez city border\n| death_date         = <!-- {{death date and age|deathyear|mm|dd|birthyear|mm|dd}} -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = Mexico, United States\n| citizenship        = \n| alma_mater         = [[Baylor University]],<br> [[San Francisco State University]]\n| occupation         = Performance Artist, Activist, Educator\n| years_active       = \n| website            = http://www.xandraibarra.com\n}}\n'''Xandra Ibarra''' (born 1979),<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://hemisphericinstitute.org/en/enc14-trasnocheo/item/2467-enc14-trasnocheo-ibarra-spictacle.html|title=La Chica Boom|last=|first=|date=|website=Hemispheric Institute|language=en-gb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> who has sometimes worked under the alias of '''La Chica Boom''', is a [[Performance Artist|performance artist]], activist, and educator. Ibarra works across video, sculpture and performance to explore abjection and joy and the borders between proper and improper racial, gender, and queer subject.<ref name=\":1\">Patel, Alpesh Kantilal.\"La Chica Boom's Failed Decolonial Spictacles.\"''HemisphericInstitute,'' 2014, hemisphericinstitute.org/hemi/en/emisferica-111-decolonial-gesture/patel. Accessed February 5, 2017.</ref> She currently based in [[Oakland, California|Oakland,]] [[California]].\n\n== About ==\nBorn in 1979 in the [[El Paso\u2013Ju\u00e1rez|El Paso/Juarez]] city border, between Mexico and the United States.<ref name=\":0\" /> She has a BA degree from [[Baylor University]]; and a MA degree from [[San Francisco State University]] (SFSU).\n\nAs of 2020, she is a [[senior lecturer]] at [[California College of the Arts]] (CCA) within the Critical Studies department.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arts.stanford.edu/event/72449/|title=Xandra Ibarra performs \u201cNude Laughing\u201d \u2013 Stanford Arts|date=2017|website=Arts, Stanford University|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25|last3=Complaints|first3=California 94305 Copyright}}</ref> She previously worked as a lecturer at San Francisco State University within the [[Ethnic studies|Ethnic Studies]] department, and an activist within the [[prison abolition movement]] and community organizing for the [[anti-rape movement]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/performance/article/Provocative-double-bill-at-CounterPulse-3878672.php|title=Provocative double bill at CounterPulse|last=Chun|first=Kimberly|date=2012-09-19|website=SFGate|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25|quote=background in prison abolition and antirape community organizing}}</ref>\n\n== Work ==\n===''Spictacles'' series (2002\u20132012)===\nIbarra performed \"spictacles\" under the moniker of La Chica Boom from 2002 until 2012.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} Spictacles, a term coined by Ibarra, \"mixed and repurpose traditional Mexican iconography alongside racist tropes within the erotic and sensual vocabulary of burlesque.<ref name=\":2\">Ramos, Ivan. \"Spic(y) Appropriation: The Gustatory Aesthetics of Xandra Ibarra (aka La Chica Boom).\"''ARARA- Art and Architecture in the Americas,'' no. 12, 2016 pp.1-18. www.essex.ac.uk/arthistory/research/pdfs/arara-issue-12/2.%20Spic(y)%20Appropriations.Ivan%20Ramos.pp.1-18.pdf. Accessed February 5, 2017.</ref> One example of such a performance is ''La Tortillera,'' exhibited starting in 2004.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacurrent.com/ArtSlut/archives/2020/03/11/the-gatekeepers-furor-over-centro-de-artes-exhibition-raises-questions-about-how-much-say-the-city-has-over-arts-content|title=The Gatekeepers: Furor Over Centro de Artes\u2019 Exhibition Raises Questions About How Much Say the City Has Over Arts Content|last=Nelson|first=Kelly Merka|website=San Antonio Current|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> \"The performance consists of Ibarra in \"traditional\" colorful Mexican tortillera dress. Although she singles out the Mexican housewife stereotype, this is also the attire that high end or \"authentic\" Mexican restaurants require of women who stand in [[Panoptica|panoptical]] view of their costumers, assuring the tortilla's faux homemade authenticity. As the performance progresses, Ibarra sheds more and more items of clothing, in the tradition of burlesque, until she dons nothing but her pasties and a [[Tapat\u00edo hot sauce|Tapat\u00edo]] bottle attached to a strap-on, which she then uses to cum on the tortilla before consuming it.\"<ref name=\":8\" /> \n\nIn the traveling art exhibition, ''XicanX: New Visions,'' curated by ''Dos Mestizx'' ([[Suzy Gonz\u00e1lez]] and Michael Menchaca) included Ibarra's ''La Tortillera'' (2004) video. When the exhibition traveled to Centro de Artes in [[San Antonio]], Texas (February 2020 \u2013 June 2020), Ibarra's artwork was abruptly removed by the City of San Antonio because they claimed \u201cobscene content.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tpr.org/post/san-antonio-arts-director-stands-city-decision-exclude-video-centro-de-artes-exhibit|title=San Antonio Arts Director Stands By City Decision To Exclude Video From Centro De Artes Exhibit|last=Morgan|first=Dominic Anthony, Jack|date=|website=Texas Public Radio (TPR)|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/arts/13875472/texas-city-censors-oakland-artist-xandra-ibarras-obscene-feminist-video|title=Texas City Censors Oakland Artist Xandra Ibarra\u2019s \u2018Obscene\u2019 Feminist Video|website=KQED|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> The City funds the art space, Centro de Artes, and it spurred the debate on the role of public support within the arts and freedom of speech.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacurrent.com/ArtSlut/archives/2020/03/11/the-gatekeepers-furor-over-centro-de-artes-exhibition-raises-questions-about-how-much-say-the-city-has-over-arts-content|title=The Gatekeepers: Furor Over Centro de Artes\u2019 Exhibition Raises Questions About How Much Say the City Has Over Arts Content|last=Nelson|first=Kelly Merka|website=San Antonio Current|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n===''Nude Laughing'' (2014, 2016)===\nXandra Ibarra performed ''Nude Laughing'' first at the [[Asian Art Museum (San Francisco)|Asian Art Museum]] (San Francisco) in 2014 and then at [[The Broad]] museum in [[Los Angeles]] in 2016, where she walks nude while laughing throughout the museum, dragging a nylon sac with paradigmatic \"white lady accoutrements\".<ref name=\":3\" /> Through this performance, Ibarra uses nudity and the sonic quality of laughter to explore the \"vexed relation racialized subjects have to not only one's own skin, but also one's own entanglements and knots (skeins) with whiteness and white womanhood.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> The piece is inspired from [[John Currin|John Currin's]] 1998 painting titled \"Laughing Nude,\" which features a nude white woman with her face caught in the middle of maniacal laughter that blurs the erotic with the grotesque.<ref name=\":3\" /> In an email to [[The Huffington Post]], Ibarra explains, \"I want to capture what I can of these white nudes in my brown figure and skin and enact a union between sound and gesture that can't be captured within a painting.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> She aims to bring the nudes to life in what she describes as the \"wrong\" body, enhancing the grotesque, tactile, and expressive dimensions of how she imagines white womanhood.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/artists-nude-laughing-exposes-much-more-than-skin_us_5706e315e4b00c2008cc31e0|title=Artist's 'Nude Laughing' Exposes Much More Than Skin (NSFW)|last=Tongco|first=Tricia|date=2016-04-08|website=The Huffington Post|access-date=2017-03-04}}</ref>\n\n===''Untitled Fucking'' (2013) ===\nThe 2013 video, ''Untitled Fucking,'' is a collaborative performance work by artists Xandra Ibarra and Amber Hawk Swanson that stages a queer intercourse between sex acts and speech acts.<ref name=\":4\">Rodriguez, Juana Maria.\"Bocados.\" ''GLQ: A Journal of Lesbian and Gay Studies'', vol. 21 no. 1, 2015, pp. 5-5. ''Project MUSE'', muse.jhu.edu/article/566787. Accessed 10 Feb. 2017.</ref> Performance studies scholar [[Juana Mar\u00eda Rodr\u00edguez|Juana Mar\u00eda Rodriguez]] examines the video to argue that \"feminism also needs to be about imagining a sexual politics that does not require the abandonment of fun and pleasure.\" She goes on to state that \"It is precisely because our sexual realities are so often steeped in abjection and violence that insisting on depictions of sex that represent the viscous substances of our lives becomes so urgent.\"<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n===''Spic Ecdysis'' (2014)===\nIn her photo essay/series Spic Ecdysis (2014) published and featured on the cover of Women and Performance Journal, Ibarra aligns herself with the figure of the cockroach and \"dwells within the limits given\u2014showing the false promise of sheer transformation.\" The term [[ecdysis]] means to shed, molt, it comes from Ancient Greek: \u1f10\u03ba\u03b4\u03cd\u03c9 (ekduo), \"to take off, strip off.\"  <ref name=\":5\">Campbell, Andy. \"The Year in Performance.\" ''Artforum: Artforum International Magazine,'' Dec. 2016, www.xandraibarra.com/artforum2016/. Accessed 22 Mar 2017.</ref> She captures the symbolic process of shedding the skin of a [[cockroach]] by laying next to costumes of her former persona La Chica Boom.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Features in academic publications ==\nIbarra has attracted the attention of various scholars of performance, gender, and race.  [[Juana Mar\u00eda Rodr\u00edguez]], a professor at the [[University of California, Berkeley]] writes about Xandra Ibarra's performance and the erotics of the [[Mexico\u2013United States border|U.S./ Mexican border]] in her book ''Sexual Futures, Queer Gestures and Other Latina Longings'' and in her essay \"Viscous Pleasures and Unruly Feminisms\" in GLQ.<ref name=\":6\">Rodr\u00edguez, Juana Mar\u00eda. \"Queer Sociality and Other Sexual Fantasies.\" ''Duke University Press'': ''GLQ: A Journal of Lesbian & Gay Studies'', vol. 17, no. 2/3, pp. 331-348, 2009, muse.jhu.edu/article/437415/pdf. Accessed 16 Feb. 2017.</ref><ref name=\":4\" /> \n\nAmber Jamilla Musser\u2019s ''Sexual Excess: Queer Femininity and Brown Jouissance'' (2018) book includes a chapter about Ibarra's collaboration with performance artist Amber Hawk Swanson, \u201cUntitled Fucking\u201d (2013). \n\nLeticia Alvarado's Abject Performances: Aesthetic Strategies in Latino Cultural Production features Ibarra's performance work \"Skins/Less Here\" (2015) on the cover and within the book.\n\nIvan Ramos, a Professor at the University of Maryland writes about La Chica Boom's performances ' Tortillera'' and ''Untitled Fucking.''<ref name=\":2\" />'' Ramos discusses Ibarra's incorporation of the symbolic [[Tapat\u00edo|Tapatio]] bottle across many of her performances and discusses how this calls attention to the history of denigration of Mexicans, carried out through the harsh criticisms of the spiciness of [[Mexican cuisine]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Ramos writes about the ways La Chica Boom appropriates and plays with the stereotypes of Mexicans as unsanitary, obnoxiously flavorful, and over sexualized, in order to dismantle them.<ref name=\":2\" /> The author connects Ibarra to the [[Chicano|Chicana/o]] art collective founded in the 1960s, [[Asco (art collective)|Asco]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* Podcast: [https://www.artpractical.com/column/living-working-jakeya-caruthers-xandra-ibarra/ Living & Working: Jakeya Caruthers & Xandra Ibarra] (2019) from [[Art Practical]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ibarra, Xandra}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:American performance artists]]\n[[Category:Decolonial feminism]]\n[[Category:Performance art in California]]\n[[Category:Queer artists]]\n[[Category:LGBT artists from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT Hispanic and Latino American people]]\n[[Category:Chicana feminists]]\n[[Category:Feminist artists]]\n[[Category:Sex-positive feminism]]\n[[Category:Decolonial artists]]\n[[Category:Artists from Oakland, California]]\n[[Category:People from El Paso, Texas]]\n[[Category:Baylor University alumni]]\n[[Category:San Francisco State University alumni]]\n[[Category:San Francisco State University faculty]]\n[[Category:California College of the Arts faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Xandra Ibarra\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| alt                = Xandra Ibarra\n| caption            = Xandra Ibarra, \"Spictacle II: La Tortillera.\" Documentation of live performance at Hemispheric Institute Encuentro, 2014\n| other_names        = La Chica Boom\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth year and age|1979}}\n| birth_place        = El Paso/Juarez city border\n| death_date         = <!-- {{death date and age|deathyear|mm|dd|birthyear|mm|dd}} -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = Mexico, United States\n| citizenship        = \n| alma_mater         = [[Baylor University]],<br> [[San Francisco State University]]\n| occupation         = Performance Artist, Activist, Educator\n| years_active       = \n| website            = http://www.xandraibarra.com\n}}\n'''Xandra Ibarra''' (born 1979),<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://hemisphericinstitute.org/en/enc14-trasnocheo/item/2467-enc14-trasnocheo-ibarra-spictacle.html|title=La Chica Boom|last=|first=|date=|website=Hemispheric Institute|language=en-gb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> who has sometimes worked under the alias of '''La Chica Boom''', is a [[Performance Artist|performance artist]], activist, and educator. Ibarra works across video, sculpture and performance to explore abjection and joy and the borders between proper and improper racial, gender, and queer subject.<ref name=\":1\">Patel, Alpesh Kantilal.\"La Chica Boom's Failed Decolonial Spictacles.\"''HemisphericInstitute,'' 2014, hemisphericinstitute.org/hemi/en/emisferica-111-decolonial-gesture/patel. Accessed February 5, 2017.</ref> She currently based in [[Oakland, California|Oakland,]] [[California]].\n\n== About ==\nBorn in 1979 in the [[El Paso\u2013Ju\u00e1rez|El Paso/Juarez]] city border, between Mexico and the United States.<ref name=\":0\" /> She has a BA degree from [[Baylor University]]; and a MA degree from [[San Francisco State University]] (SFSU).{{When|date=February 2020}} She performed in [[musical theatre]] in early adulthood, and learned [[burlesque]] from a performer named Sheu Sheu Le\u2019Haure.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.artpractical.com/feature/interview_with_la_chica_boom/|title=From the Archives: Worse Than Queer, Interview with La Chica Boom|last=Martinez|first=Marta|date=2011-04-11|website=Art Practical|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25|quote=\"At this time, I was also participating in the sex-work industry. So a lot of my thoughts were around and about sex and sexuality and power and failure.\" \"I was thinking about sex, sexuality, and sexual violence in particular because I organized with an anti-rape agenda with INCITE! and CARA (Communities Against Rape and Abuse) at the time.\" \"Her name was Sheu Sheu Le\u2019Haure, and she took me under her wing and showed me a little bit of burlesque.\"}}</ref> Around the same time she was active in the sex-worker industry, as well as with the national anti-violence groups [[Incite!]] and CARA (Communities Against Rape and Abuse).<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nAs of 2020, she is a [[senior lecturer]] at [[California College of the Arts]] (CCA) within the Critical Studies department.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arts.stanford.edu/event/72449/|title=Xandra Ibarra performs \u201cNude Laughing\u201d \u2013 Stanford Arts|date=2017|website=Arts, Stanford University|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25|last3=Complaints|first3=California 94305 Copyright}}</ref> She previously worked as a lecturer at San Francisco State University within the [[Ethnic studies|Ethnic Studies]] department, and an activist within the [[prison abolition movement]] and community organizing for the [[anti-rape movement]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/performance/article/Provocative-double-bill-at-CounterPulse-3878672.php|title=Provocative double bill at CounterPulse|last=Chun|first=Kimberly|date=2012-09-19|website=SFGate|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25|quote=background in prison abolition and antirape community organizing}}</ref>\n\n== Work ==\n===''Spictacles'' series (2002\u20132012)===\nIbarra performed \"spictacles\" under the moniker of La Chica Boom from 2002 until 2012.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} Spictacles, a term coined by Ibarra, \"mixed and repurpose traditional Mexican iconography alongside racist tropes within the erotic and sensual vocabulary of burlesque.<ref name=\":2\">Ramos, Ivan. \"Spic(y) Appropriation: The Gustatory Aesthetics of Xandra Ibarra (aka La Chica Boom).\"''ARARA- Art and Architecture in the Americas,'' no. 12, 2016 pp.1-18. www.essex.ac.uk/arthistory/research/pdfs/arara-issue-12/2.%20Spic(y)%20Appropriations.Ivan%20Ramos.pp.1-18.pdf. Accessed February 5, 2017.</ref> One example of such a performance is ''La Tortillera,'' exhibited starting in 2004.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacurrent.com/ArtSlut/archives/2020/03/11/the-gatekeepers-furor-over-centro-de-artes-exhibition-raises-questions-about-how-much-say-the-city-has-over-arts-content|title=The Gatekeepers: Furor Over Centro de Artes\u2019 Exhibition Raises Questions About How Much Say the City Has Over Arts Content|last=Nelson|first=Kelly Merka|website=San Antonio Current|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> \"The performance consists of Ibarra in \"traditional\" colorful Mexican tortillera dress. Although she singles out the Mexican housewife stereotype, this is also the attire that high end or \"authentic\" Mexican restaurants require of women who stand in [[Panoptica|panoptical]] view of their costumers, assuring the tortilla's faux homemade authenticity. As the performance progresses, Ibarra sheds more and more items of clothing, in the tradition of burlesque, until she dons nothing but her pasties and a [[Tapat\u00edo hot sauce|Tapat\u00edo]] bottle attached to a strap-on, which she then uses to cum on the tortilla before consuming it.\"<ref name=\":8\" /> \n\nIn the traveling art exhibition, ''XicanX: New Visions,'' curated by ''Dos Mestizx'' ([[Suzy Gonz\u00e1lez]] and Michael Menchaca) included Ibarra's ''La Tortillera'' (2004) video. When the exhibition traveled to Centro de Artes in [[San Antonio]], Texas (February 2020 \u2013 June 2020), Ibarra's artwork was abruptly removed by the City of San Antonio because they claimed \u201cobscene content.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tpr.org/post/san-antonio-arts-director-stands-city-decision-exclude-video-centro-de-artes-exhibit|title=San Antonio Arts Director Stands By City Decision To Exclude Video From Centro De Artes Exhibit|last=Morgan|first=Dominic Anthony, Jack|date=|website=Texas Public Radio (TPR)|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/arts/13875472/texas-city-censors-oakland-artist-xandra-ibarras-obscene-feminist-video|title=Texas City Censors Oakland Artist Xandra Ibarra\u2019s \u2018Obscene\u2019 Feminist Video|website=KQED|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> The City funds the art space, Centro de Artes, and it spurred the debate on the role of public support within the arts and freedom of speech.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacurrent.com/ArtSlut/archives/2020/03/11/the-gatekeepers-furor-over-centro-de-artes-exhibition-raises-questions-about-how-much-say-the-city-has-over-arts-content|title=The Gatekeepers: Furor Over Centro de Artes\u2019 Exhibition Raises Questions About How Much Say the City Has Over Arts Content|last=Nelson|first=Kelly Merka|website=San Antonio Current|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n===''Nude Laughing'' (2014, 2016)===\nXandra Ibarra performed ''Nude Laughing'' first at the [[Asian Art Museum (San Francisco)|Asian Art Museum]] (San Francisco) in 2014 and then at [[The Broad]] museum in [[Los Angeles]] in 2016, where she walks nude while laughing throughout the museum, dragging a nylon sac with paradigmatic \"white lady accoutrements\".<ref name=\":3\" /> Through this performance, Ibarra uses nudity and the sonic quality of laughter to explore the \"vexed relation racialized subjects have to not only one's own skin, but also one's own entanglements and knots (skeins) with whiteness and white womanhood.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> The piece is inspired from [[John Currin|John Currin's]] 1998 painting titled \"Laughing Nude,\" which features a nude white woman with her face caught in the middle of maniacal laughter that blurs the erotic with the grotesque.<ref name=\":3\" /> In an email to [[The Huffington Post]], Ibarra explains, \"I want to capture what I can of these white nudes in my brown figure and skin and enact a union between sound and gesture that can't be captured within a painting.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> She aims to bring the nudes to life in what she describes as the \"wrong\" body, enhancing the grotesque, tactile, and expressive dimensions of how she imagines white womanhood.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/artists-nude-laughing-exposes-much-more-than-skin_us_5706e315e4b00c2008cc31e0|title=Artist's 'Nude Laughing' Exposes Much More Than Skin (NSFW)|last=Tongco|first=Tricia|date=2016-04-08|website=The Huffington Post|access-date=2017-03-04}}</ref>\n\n===''Untitled Fucking'' (2013) ===\nThe 2013 video, ''Untitled Fucking,'' is a collaborative performance work by artists Xandra Ibarra and Amber Hawk Swanson that stages a queer intercourse between sex acts and speech acts.<ref name=\":4\">Rodriguez, Juana Maria.\"Bocados.\" ''GLQ: A Journal of Lesbian and Gay Studies'', vol. 21 no. 1, 2015, pp. 5-5. ''Project MUSE'', muse.jhu.edu/article/566787. Accessed 10 Feb. 2017.</ref> Performance studies scholar [[Juana Mar\u00eda Rodr\u00edguez|Juana Mar\u00eda Rodriguez]] examines the video to argue that \"feminism also needs to be about imagining a sexual politics that does not require the abandonment of fun and pleasure.\" She goes on to state that \"It is precisely because our sexual realities are so often steeped in abjection and violence that insisting on depictions of sex that represent the viscous substances of our lives becomes so urgent.\"<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n===''Spic Ecdysis'' (2014)===\nIn her photo essay/series Spic Ecdysis (2014) published and featured on the cover of Women and Performance Journal, Ibarra aligns herself with the figure of the cockroach and \"dwells within the limits given\u2014showing the false promise of sheer transformation.\" The term [[ecdysis]] means to shed, molt, it comes from Ancient Greek: \u1f10\u03ba\u03b4\u03cd\u03c9 (ekduo), \"to take off, strip off.\"  <ref name=\":5\">Campbell, Andy. \"The Year in Performance.\" ''Artforum: Artforum International Magazine,'' Dec. 2016, www.xandraibarra.com/artforum2016/. Accessed 22 Mar 2017.</ref> She captures the symbolic process of shedding the skin of a [[cockroach]] by laying next to costumes of her former persona La Chica Boom.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Features in academic publications ==\nIbarra has attracted the attention of various scholars of performance, gender, and race.  [[Juana Mar\u00eda Rodr\u00edguez]], a professor at the [[University of California, Berkeley]] writes about Xandra Ibarra's performance and the erotics of the [[Mexico\u2013United States border|U.S./ Mexican border]] in her book ''Sexual Futures, Queer Gestures and Other Latina Longings'' and in her essay \"Viscous Pleasures and Unruly Feminisms\" in GLQ.<ref name=\":6\">Rodr\u00edguez, Juana Mar\u00eda. \"Queer Sociality and Other Sexual Fantasies.\" ''Duke University Press'': ''GLQ: A Journal of Lesbian & Gay Studies'', vol. 17, no. 2/3, pp. 331-348, 2009, muse.jhu.edu/article/437415/pdf. Accessed 16 Feb. 2017.</ref><ref name=\":4\" /> \n\nAmber Jamilla Musser\u2019s ''Sexual Excess: Queer Femininity and Brown Jouissance'' (2018) book includes a chapter about Ibarra's collaboration with performance artist Amber Hawk Swanson, \u201cUntitled Fucking\u201d (2013). \n\nLeticia Alvarado's Abject Performances: Aesthetic Strategies in Latino Cultural Production features Ibarra's performance work \"Skins/Less Here\" (2015) on the cover and within the book.\n\nIvan Ramos, a Professor at the University of Maryland writes about La Chica Boom's performances ' Tortillera'' and ''Untitled Fucking.''<ref name=\":2\" />'' Ramos discusses Ibarra's incorporation of the symbolic [[Tapat\u00edo|Tapatio]] bottle across many of her performances and discusses how this calls attention to the history of denigration of Mexicans, carried out through the harsh criticisms of the spiciness of [[Mexican cuisine]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Ramos writes about the ways La Chica Boom appropriates and plays with the stereotypes of Mexicans as unsanitary, obnoxiously flavorful, and over sexualized, in order to dismantle them.<ref name=\":2\" /> The author connects Ibarra to the [[Chicano|Chicana/o]] art collective founded in the 1960s, [[Asco (art collective)|Asco]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* Podcast: [https://www.artpractical.com/column/living-working-jakeya-caruthers-xandra-ibarra/ Living & Working: Jakeya Caruthers & Xandra Ibarra] (2019) from [[Art Practical]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ibarra, Xandra}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:American performance artists]]\n[[Category:Decolonial feminism]]\n[[Category:Performance art in California]]\n[[Category:Queer artists]]\n[[Category:LGBT artists from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT Hispanic and Latino American people]]\n[[Category:Chicana feminists]]\n[[Category:Feminist artists]]\n[[Category:Sex-positive feminism]]\n[[Category:Decolonial artists]]\n[[Category:Artists from Oakland, California]]\n[[Category:People from El Paso, Texas]]\n[[Category:Baylor University alumni]]\n[[Category:San Francisco State University alumni]]\n[[Category:San Francisco State University faculty]]\n[[Category:California College of the Arts faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Gregoriagregoria21", "label": "safe", "comment": "Please stop outing people on wikipedia who work in the sex industry without their permission. I will delete this page if I am not allowed to maintain privacy for my worker identity.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xandra_Ibarra"}
